The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that the health care bill signed by Barack Obama is in line with the Constitution, a major victory for the Obama administration.
By a vote of 5:4, the court ruled that the individual order of the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act – which orders citizens to purchase health insurance by 2014, otherwise they are at risk of paying a fine – do not contradict the Constitution on the basis of government tax authority.
Court President John Roberts stood on the side of the four more liberal members of the court, while Judges Scalia, Thomas, Alito and Kennedy were in opposition.
The court also supported the remaining parts of the 2700-page bill and further ruled that the legal requirement for health care, which orders states to extend the possibility of obtaining sickness insurance, otherwise there is a risk of losing all funding for sickness insurance from federal sources, not coercive and in violation of the Constitution.
The lawsuit was brought by 26 states and the National Federation of Independent Enterprises in order to block this law.
During the 2012 primaries, the bill strongly rejected each of the major Republican candidates, including presumed proposed candidate Mitt Romney.
