Muhammad Morsi has taken the inaugural oath, but his triumphant day is hard to end with political unrest in Egypt.
ISLAMIST Muhammad Morsi promised a “new Egypt” when he was inaugurated as the country’s first free president, after Hosni Mubarak, who had been deposed 16 months earlier.
In his appointment before the High Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and the fifth Egyptian head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy approximately 60 years ago.
He took an oath before 18 judges dressed in black gowns in a mansion built overlooking the Nile, which resembles an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are aiming for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic," Morsi said during a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
“The Egyptian people today laid the foundation for a new life – absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,” said Morsi, a 60-year-old engineer trained in the U.S. and a member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been the target of sharp attacks by individual governments for most of its 84 years since its inception as an illegal organization.
When Morsi arrived in a small column of cars shortly after 11 a.m. local time, hundreds of soldiers and police officers were guarding the building.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered in front of the courthouse to celebrate the president, and unlike the presidential pomp of Mubarak's period, traffic was only briefly stopped so that the column could pass through a usually busy road connecting the city center with the suburbs in the south.
The personal prestige of Morsi, mockingly referred to as the Muslim Brotherhood’s non-charismatic “reserve tire”, has grown sharply since his victory and his Friday speech, which aimed to present him not only as a candidate for the Islamists, but also of all those who want to bring to an end the revolt against the authoritarian Mubarak.
"Egypt is now a civil, national, constitutional and modern state," Morsi, dressed in a blue social suit with a red tie to the judges in a wood-panled chamber where he took the oath.
Mursi later travelled to Cairo University, where he was due to deliver an inaugural speech.
