Is the European elite ready for trade with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with a promise to bring businesses together and define what changes in the relationship with the EU British entrepreneurs and job-creating companies want to see.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey, in which we asked leading British entrepreneurs about their views on Britain, trade and the EU.
YouGov interviewed 1,000 leading entrepreneurs representing British businesses of all sizes and from different sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We have found that the vast majority of businesses are now trying to export outside Europe and focus on countries that are modernising and growing while EU states are stagnant.
They want to see the government prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than get bogged down in the long and strenuous process of reforming mysterious European institutions.
When we asked about their views on specific political areas – from monopolistic regulations to product laws – most entrepreneurs expressed the view that control of these key competences should be returned to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, and entrepreneurs said that the costs of Brussels regulations now outweigh the benefits of being part of the European business area – 40 percent of large enterprises, traditionally the most pro-European companies, expressed their approval.
And finally, our survey of business leaders revealed the most eloquent knowledge, namely that a clear majority wants Britain to strive to change the treaty and the relationship with the EU, which should be based on trade, not politics.
The findings, identified by businesses of different sizes and core business groups, show that the business sector is pushing for a “meaningful change” that will bring influence back to Britain.
There's a lot at stake - achieving a treaty change and a better deal for Britain can make a gain of up to 16% when voting in a referendum to remain in the EU.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate: this survey shows that the British trade supports his plan to amend the terms of British membership of the EU.
It also shows that the business sector expects this amendment to mark a significant shift from the current balance of forces back towards Britain.
A better deal for Britain is perhaps, and given how the eurozone is embarking on a journey beyond a closer economic and fiscal union, even more urgently.
Jobs and growth in Britain must be a priority, and as the results of our survey show, for business this means re-focusing on trade and a fundamental change in Brussels' regulatory approach.
