Frontier Airlines is about to charge for carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge an amount of up to USD 100 on its flights for storing hand luggage on board.
Frontier Airlines plans to introduce a fee of up to USD 100 for hand luggage and USD 2 for coffee or soda, although in their announcement on Wednesday they said passengers would be able to keep the entire can.
The new baggage charge applies to luggage in the upper storage compartment, so small luggage under the seat will continue to be free.
Frontier says it will charge USD 25 if the fee is paid in advance, and USD 100 if passengers with payment are waiting until they arrive at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the hundred-dollar fee was intended to encourage passengers to take care of the payment in advance.
"We don't want to collect that fee," she said.
Airlines began charging for the first and second handed baggage in 2008.
Passengers tried to avoid these fees and stuffed into hand luggage hidden in storage as much as they could, so that space was often lacking in that space.
Fees are one of the ways to teach passengers to take less things on board.
O'Malley said the point of this new fee is not to actually raise more money.
The point is that Frontier’s most loyal customers have made it quite clear that finding space in the upper storage space is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who purchase tickets on the company's website will not pay.
This means that one passenger in a queue at Frontier’s gate can bring luggage for which they pay nothing, while the other passenger queues for the same luggage pays USD 100.
O'Malley said the website and check-in procedures will be adjusted to ensure that passengers learn about the fee before they arrive at the gate.
Frontier’s new baggage fee will not be in effect until summer, but the date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage charges and other fees, but airlines love them.
They argue that the handling of luggage costs money, and passengers who request the service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see an additional baggage fee as a sign that airlines are trying to withdraw enough money to cover the cost of air traffic after years of losses.
However, most did not apply to carry-on baggage charges.
Spirit Airlines was the first to charge for hand luggage three years ago, and another low-cost company, Allegiant Air, followed its example later.
The only company that also has such fees is Hungary's Wizz Air, says air transport adviser Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
In his December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit's carry-on baggage charge would bring US$50 million annually.
Sorensen, a former executive of Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and marveled at what he saw at the gate when passengers were met with an unusual Spirit fee for hand luggage.
"Getting on a plane was the smoothest I've ever seen in my aviation career," he said.
I expected to see a gnashing of teeth and a fight at the gate.
The plane was full, he said, "and the boarding took place in a flash."
The Frontier also applies fees for coffee, tea, soda and juice, following Spirit’s example.
Frontier said passengers who get lemonade or juice could keep the entire can and the coffee would be replenished for free.
The water will continue to be given free of charge.
US Airways briefly tried to impose beverage charges in 2008 but backed away from it seven months later after passenger complaints, and no other major airline imitated it.
Frontier's last move to charge for hand luggage if the passenger does not purchase a flight directly from that airline is its latest effort to direct customers directly to its website.
Airlines pay online travel retailers, such as Orbitz, from USD 10 to 25 for each ticket sold.
This has given all airlines the incentive to lead passengers to purchase directly from them, rather than do so through online travel agencies.
However, Frontier has gone the furthest in this area.
In September, she began giving customers who bought through an internet travel agency, just half the miles under the loyalty program.
On Wednesday, she cropped the reward for flying miles to 25 percent of the miles from the trip.
So the journey with Frontier, a long 1000 miles purchased through an internet travel agency, means a reward of 250 miles.
The company also allows customers to choose their seat in advance only if they make the purchase directly through Frontier’s website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in its home city of Denver, but its business is starting to shrink and lose money.
According to financial results reported on Wednesday by corporate partner Republic Airways Holdings, sales fell 9 percent and transport capacity shrunk by nearly 13 percent in the first quarter
The company Republic is trying to solve the financial problems of Frontier by selling this airline.
