And he founded the nonprofit organization ASCOVIME, whose members visit rural areas over the weekend, where they provide free medical care.
Since 2008, almost 32 000 people have helped with their group of volunteers.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people are packed into deliveries, attached to the rooftops of medical supplies and travel through rough terrain to villages that need help.
They are not always accompanied by happiness.
More than once, vehicles have to push through the river and mud.
But when they arrive, they get a welcome as real heroes: a feast, singing and dancing, and the best accommodation the community has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is truly a reason to celebrate, and Bwelle – with his broad smile and unbridled energy – is very willing to engage in local merriment.
The next day, the team begins to treat hundreds of patients.
"We have 500 patients on every quest," says Bwelle.
They come to the village from a 60-kilometer radius, on foot.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide various medical assistance.
Many are treated with malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can get crutches or donated glasses or a free birth certificate – a document that is required by the school, but which many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Surgeries are usually done in the school building, at City Hall or at home; after surgery, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery site to make room for the next patient.
Using the light from the generator, the operating room and the hygiene equipment of Bwelle and his volunteers, they work until the early hours of the morning.
It's exhausting, but the village musicians usually help the team not lose motivation.
"To stay up and keep working, they play the drums all night," Bwelle says.
On Sunday, the team will head back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group – consisting of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – performed 700 free operations last year and realizes that their help can mean a lot to locals.
One man said he would be able to work again after the hernia surgery.
"That will change our family's future," the man said.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and the work of a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works at night for private medical clinics around the city of Yaounde.
He says it is this second work that finances about 60% of his nonprofit activities; the rest is covered by private contributions.
“I’m not sure when she’s sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who studies medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia for the second year and volunteers for the Bwelle group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can do those campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who came from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, this is a great practice they wouldn't get at home.
"We thoroughly washed Dr. Bwell's hands and removed bloodstains or held his tools," O'Malley says.
As a second-year medical student in America, you will never experience that.
Students volunteers usually pay their way to Cameroon alone and often arrive with donated medical supplies.
But once they arrive in Yaounde, food, transportation and study are provided by Bwelle.
"No doubt he's a hero," says O'Malley.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwelle, constant harness is not a burden.
Helping others to live happier, fulfilling the promise he made to his father is something that brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," Bwelle says.
And I think about my father.
I hope he can see what I'm doing.
