With the growing misery of the middle class, pawnshops in Singapore are experiencing a flourish
At a pawnshop in the Bendemeer shopping centre in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga stops a gold bracelet, ring and earrings to pay her daughter tuition fees.
"My husband and I just bought a house and I put all my money on it," says Ms. Amirthalinga.
Although she receives 2400 dollars (3000 SGDs) each month as an administrator, and her husband also works, family monthly income is inadequate, she says.
Indeed, demand across areas in Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is that ValueMax, where a woman conducts her transaction, became the third pawnbrower on the list on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Stopping jewelry is not only a quick way to borrow cash – 1300 SGD in the case of Mrs. Amirthalinga – but it is also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Pawnshops in Singapore routinely apply an annual percentage rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent rate offered by United Overseas Bank, a local bank with a branch in the same shopping centre.
However, pawnshops have the advantage of not requiring verification of a person (payment history) or proof of income, and can provide a loan faster than banks.
And that's why, as families feel pressure over rising living costs and rising household and consumer debt, millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops.
After five years of massive growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans backed by a loose monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to deal with the deteriorating financial situation.
This week, the credit rating agency Standard & Poor's cited the increasing use of household credit primarily because of rising rents as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
She said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia due to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the forefront of the rankings with a ratio of 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists also feared a high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week just so came out of a technical recession.
On Thursday, the data showed continued weak exports and a weakening of consumer demand.
"The bottom line is that with rising costs, people from medium to low [income scale] will try to supplement their income wherever they can," said Song Seng Wun, an economist at Malaysian bank CIMB.
Historically, high gold prices have contributed to people hastily stopping their personal property over the past two years and taking the opportunity to exchange their family jewellery for cash.
About 70 percent of the items stopped in 200 city pawnshops make up gold.
People say: the price of gold looks good, we stop Grandma's gold necklace and get it back next month.
The largest pawnshop operator in Thailand, EasyMoney, has seen up to 20 percent increases in recent months in the number of customers using its pawnshops.
The growth in the pawn industry is so large that ValueMax, a branch operator in downtown Bendemeer and 15 similar in Singapore, plans to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where it has four offices – but also outside Asia, says ValueMax Executive Director Yeah Lee Ching.
The company will fund it by using 60 percent of the 66 million SGD it acquired this week on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some discount lenders have come under fire for high interest rates, Ms. Yeah says the pledge not only offers lower rates than other lenders, but it also doesn't directly increase debt.
"Customers stop items they already own, and the monetization of personal property does not increase the household's debt," he says.
In the company, the pledge of property is increasingly accepted as a means of securing short-term, secure financing.
Moreover, among those who use pawnshops, it is not just people in financial distress.
The wealthy people of Singapore also use the ValueMax branch when they stop gold rods or Rolex watches, and can thus get up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Our customers are from all possible circumstances.
"They include wealthy individuals who need to borrow for the short term because of their bold business or investment, or small businesses that need help resolving problems in their cash flow," says Ms. Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money as quickly as possible.
