This is the true European story: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally failed.
Due to the euro crisis, the so-called Europe Project is officially dead.
Across Europe, the influence of the party dedicated to resistance to the EU or the abolition of the euro as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded this year – came out of nowhere and already in the September federal elections captured almost five million votes, essentially “sweeping out” of the Bundestag the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats).
On home soil, there has always been resistance to a plan to create a federal Europe.
But the current economic crisis has become a defining moment.
The austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, together with the straitjacket strung to national economies through clinging to the common currency, has led many people to believe that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments managing a high budget deficit – this was only true in the case of Greece.
Rather, it is a system of the euro that blocks its members at exchange rates favorable to German exporters – and that is what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the domestic currency, southern Europe has a disadvantage in the area of domestic production compared to Germany.
The only help is to cut revenues and public spending – which Germany encourages.
The current problems with the budget and currency are due to the deeper cause of European malaise.
As a result of the “green” energy policy backed by Brussels – a code to support French and German companies at the cost of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gasoline than is the case in the United States.
This is a paralyzing disadvantage in the cost area, as we have already seen in the case of Grangemouth.
Even all the wage freezes in the world would not avert the slamming of the European petrochemical industry by cheap shale oil from the US.
The result is a smoldering revolt, especially in France, once an enthusiastic supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool that will keep Germany at bay and allow Paris to stand in the world to the level of Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a political legitimacy card and has enforced its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the worn-out French economy to its fate.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right wing, the anti-European National Front, has just won a major additional election and pushed the ruling Socialists to third place.
The front is now with 24% of the vote the most popular party in France - an early warning to British Labour that they cannot conclude that the splitting of the right will automatically have a positive effect on the left.
How does Le Pen handle her newly acquired popularity among the white working class?
She would like to use the European elections next year to create an anti-European bloc operating against the common currency across the European Parliament.
If anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is likely, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time in its history.
In doing so, it occurs to me that in the foreseeable future, the growing anti-European feeling and attitude against the common currency will come together and the euro will be destroyed.
The EU will not disappear, but rather transform into something looser in the sense of “Europe (sovereign) peoples”, which General de Gaulle preferred.
Germany and several of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project and cling to the United States.
However, Washington's increased interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to the Atlantic cold.
Where will Scotland be?
We can choose to be an area (in principle) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – this includes the possibility of announcing to Berlin and Brussels when to let us be.
I suppose Scotland would do well in a relaxed order of Europe, provided it retains its own currency.
