The researchers explained more about how tail movements were related to the dog's mood
Previous research has shown that joyful dogs wag their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs wave their tails mostly to the left.
Now, however, scientists say other dogs can record these subtle differences in tail movement and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trento, said: "In humans, it is well known that the left and right sides of the brain have different links to stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions."
We tried to observe the same thing in other species.
He added that, as is the case in humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that these two hemispheres play a different role in emotions.
In an effort to get more information on how dogs respond to the disproportionate wagging of other dogs' tails, researchers monitored animals that watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side, and other times to the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We have screened dog films about dogs - either in the natural version or in the form of a silhouette - to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we have also been able to adjust the movement of the tail and represent it more to the right or left."
When the animals saw an otherwise bland dog moving its tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), it remained absolutely calm.
But when she noticed the filming of the tail mostly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging his tail), their heart rate increased and the animals seemed uncertain.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think dogs would communicate with each other consciously through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they have to and do not have to look out for.
He said: "If you encounter dogs several times and the movement of their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with rather friendly behavior, and movement to the right breeds less friendly behavior, you will respond based on this experience."
Researchers say the findings can help dog owners, vets and trainers better understand their animals' emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a university teacher at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine whether the left and right sides were important to dogs.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found out that dogs were turning their heads to the left when they were watching an aggressive dog, and on the right, looking at a cheerful dog.
And in another expert treatise from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "Dogs were more likely to be familiar with the dog robot when it was wagging its tail to the left than the right, when they were becoming more uncertain, exactly the opposite of the Italian study."
According to him, the difference can be due to the fact that dogs in these different studios did not interpret animals in movies or dog robots completely like dogs.
He explained that a study could help on how dogs react to real dogs.
“Although in the case of many different mammals there is strong evidence that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won't be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and other times to the other.
