The Royal Commission learned that two employees of the Christian Young Men's Association (YMCA) had been charged before the lawsuits against Jonathan Lord
The Royal Commission on Child Sex Abuse learned that before charges were filed against child educator Jonathan Lord of the city of Caringbah in 2011, two employees of the Christian Young Men's Association (YMCA) in New South Wales were accused of sexually abusing children.
But it was said before the commission that in its opening statement to the commission, the association said it had never addressed a case of sexual abuse of a child in its organization.
Chief Executive Phillip Hare was asked about a case in which one of the YMCA's employees was charged with misdemeanors involving child pornography, and another when a gym teacher at Caringbah of the YMCA was convicted in 1991 of sexual harassment of children he had in his care.
Mr. Hare told Gaili Furness, the commission's adviser, that he knew about the first case, but not about the second.
He admitted that YMCA's initial statement was also inaccurate when it stated that external audits were carried out at YMCA, which recognized the organization as a leading advocate of children's rights.
The evidence presented by the commission indicates that YMCA was warned that in an audit by the Ministry of Education and Society from August this year, it received the second lowest of the four possible assessments.
Mr. Hare, who began working with the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that the management had failed from him downwards when he accepted Mr Lord without making sure that the staff were aware of the obligation to report violations of child safety rules.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexually harassing 12 boys he committed during his two years working at the YMCA.
He was jailed for at least six years.
But Mr. Hare rejected claims that the YMCA had a cultural problem that prevented the staff from reporting the child safety breach by Mr Lord.
Staff members gave evidence that they witnessed such violations, including that the Lord was alone with the children, guarding them privately, letting them sit with them on their laps, telling them that he liked them, and letting them play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Ockwell, who was Lord's subordinate and asked to train for the safety of the children because she was concerned about his behavior, testified that Jacqui Barnat, head of services to children at the YMCA in Caringbah, who was Lord's superior, was "very intimidating and often find it difficult to talk to him about anything."
The chief executive said he did not accept the staff's evidence that they felt uneasy if they were to contact their superiors and report the deeds.
Instead, he said their friendship with the Lord had obscured their judgment and therefore did not report the problem.
Mr. Hare said that he had communicated to the YMCA Board in New South Wales that the lessons of Jonathan Lord's "case for the organisation" were that the staff had "not filed a report" and the board agreed with him on this.
Mr. Hare said the decision to let the staff sign the confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations surfaced, made the general manager for child service at YMCA, Liam Whitley.
He said the goal was to avoid damaging the evidence, but it was "overly zealous" and poorly executed.
Expert on child sexual abuse Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University told the commission that the YMCA in New South Wales was not an organisation that would be safe for children between 2009 and 2011.
He said there were serious problems in recruiting, screening, incorporation, training and staff management.
The hearing was adjourned to December 20.
