FAA: Air travelers can now use technological gains on aircraft (but not allowed to call from their mobile phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices "from gateway to gate" - in addition to calling from their mobile phones - to read, play games, watch movies and listen to music based on the eagerly awaited new rules issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) on Thursday.
Passengers should not expect the changes to occur immediately.
How quickly the change will be introduced will vary by airline, FAA administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA how much their aircraft comply with the new rules and that they have updated the cabin crew training manuals and equipment storage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices on aircraft.
Among the companies that have already submitted the plans are Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of such a plan, we can improve the widespread use of electronic devices very quickly," the FAA said in a statement.
Passengers are currently required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft door closes.
They can't turn them on until the plane reaches an altitude of 3 kilometers and the captain doesn't issue a warrant.
Passengers are expected to shut down their devices again when the plane is down to land, and not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected against electronic interference can allow their passengers to use their devices during take-off, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft, which have been modified to allow passengers to use Wifi at higher altitudes, are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Stewards Association, welcomed the changes.
“Once the new rules are safely introduced – and we work closely with transport companies – it will be a success,” Glading said.
We are, frankly, tired of looking like “guardians.”
However, surfing the Internet, sending emails and texting or downloading data will continue to be banned below 3 kilometers of altitude, the agency said.
Passengers will be notified to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to air mode.
So still no Words with friends, an online scrabble game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011 when he was, as is well known, thrown off an American Airlines plane because he refused to shut down his device when the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops will still have to be stored because of fears that they could injure someone if they fly around the cabin.
Calls from mobile phones will continue to be banned on board.
