Six out of ten companies are preparing for the new Civil Code
Six out of ten companies are preparing for the upcoming effectiveness of the new Civil Code and the Corporations Act from 1 January 2014.
Just eight percent of the firms surveyed said they did not address the matters related to both key codes in their company at all.
This is according to a survey by the law firm Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal, which found the views of 108 Czech companies.
In the context of the approaching effective date of both key codes, only now at the last minute many managers are beginning to realize what a significant impact they can have on the business of their companies.
In our opinion, the biggest changes in private law in the last 50 years will affect all citizens and companies in the Czech Republic.
Because of the lavishing of politicians, the business sector has long lived in uncertainty about whether revolutionary changes will eventually occur or not.
"But they now have only a few weeks left to make the transition to a new right for their companies without complications," said Jan Spáčil, partner of Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal.
Of the 61 percent of companies intensively engaged in the new codes, 26 percent said their firms had already taken all necessary measures to be prepared in a timely manner.
Furthermore, 35 percent of the companies of this number are preparing to take the necessary measures in the near future.
Against this, one in five companies has not yet dealt with recodifications, yet it has a concrete idea of how to prepare for them.
A total of 11 percent have no opinion and cannot assess the issue.
Just eight percent of companies admit that they have not yet addressed matters related to recodifications.
The most important legal topic related to the new Civil Code is the conclusion of new contracts (21 percent) for the largest number of companies interviewed, followed by a solution to the terms and conditions (16 percent) and changes in the Land Registry and in liability for damage (after ten percent).
In the case of contracts, one of the most important innovations of the whole recodification will take place, namely the unification of the regulation of contracts only within the framework of the new Civil Code.
The current parallel regulation in the Civil and Commercial Code will expire, as a result of which the contract law should become clearer for citizens and entrepreneurs.
"In the case of entrepreneurs, the new regulation will offer many innovations with an emphasis on greater freedom of organization of relationships," said Lukáš Poddán, attorney at Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal.
In connection with the Corporations Act, almost a quarter of companies consider the issue of increasing the responsibility of statutory bodies to be the most important topic.
Furthermore, the topics related to changes in the convening and the course of the general meeting (15 percent) and the representation of the company (14 percent) follow.
The new legislation means a tightening of obligations and possible impacts for statutory bodies, especially when companies are at risk of bankruptcy or getting into it.
"In practice, this means that if the board members and the executives of the companies do not act with the care of a proper manager and do not avert the impending bankruptcy of the company, they may lose the benefit earned for the performance of the office for the last two years," Spáčil added.
