New nicotine vaccine may take away the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that can take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect the mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
Before the human trials, more tests need to be carried out, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of the Weill Cornell Medical School in New York says the first indications are good.
“We strongly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhausted all methods available in the market today, but have found that their nicotine dependence is so strong to overcome all current approaches,” said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been compiled to carry genetic information to produce anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to produce a smooth stream of these antibodies.
The antibodies chase all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
During the tests of the vaccinated mouse, to which nicotine was subsequently supplied, they continued their normal activities.
But mice that were not vaccinated “calmed down,” the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines have failed because they contained antibodies.
Injections had to be given so often to maintain sufficient levels of antibodies, so they proved expensive and impractical.
The cost of new vaccines should be much lower because they turn liver cells into factories to make antibodies.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines are completely safe for people, they could be given to children before they feel like trying a cigarette, and this would prevent nicotine addiction.
However, it would be much more likely to be used by smokers to stop.
"They'll know that if they start smoking again, they won't enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that will help them get rid of that habit," he said.
British scientists have said the results were interesting, but cautioned that further research was needed.
A desperate cry from Obama's constituent
I voted for Obama twice – I shared hopes of a possible change
He says Obama's sincere efforts have thwarted the Republican Party's obstruction
Obstructionist policy cannot excuse the hardships of the Obama health care website or drone strikes
The 2008 Obama campaign's memoir is a sad reminder of what could have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is studying medicine at Harvard for the second year running.
I'm reading a very sad book these days.
I thought this book would encourage me during the grim days of my second year at medical school and restore a little hope in me.
It's called "The Audacy to Win" and is a memory of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish the patient's assessments in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics has inspired millions of people and the speeches have taken your breath away.
The election ended in overwhelming superiority, and television news forced us to reflect on the historical value of this moment.
My classmates were crying with joy, and my parents kept the newspaper they could get.
A young team of visionaries headed to the White House, and the nation was ready for change.
During the 2008 office, Obama had 82 percent support.
And here I'm closing the book.
Going to the present is a harsh awakening, like waking up from a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic days – they seem to be distant memories, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years after I threw my first ballot, there were indeed changes.
It was definitely nothing I had imagined.
I recognize that Obama has achieved a number of great and diverse achievements – from the law on available care to the withdrawal of our troops from Iraq and the end of politics “not to ask anything, not to say anything” to the killing of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructions have reversed so many efforts to move our nation forward: among other things, it is immigration reform, the possibility of the public to choose health care and the closure of the base in Guantánamo.
But after many situations where I have defended the Obama administration in front of colleagues and friends, I have reached the absolute limit when it comes to the explanations they can provide.
I found myself in a place of political despair.
The obstructions of Republicans cannot explain consent to eavesdropping on foreign leaders or with drone strikes that kill innocent children overseas.
It cannot be explained by the fact that the National Security Agency collects data on the private life of Americans, nor that it persecutes those who reveal the wrong conduct of the government.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, a U.S. citizen, without a proper trial, or for curtailing public contributions and spending during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify the findings of a report that White House efforts to silence the media are "the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration."
And most recently, they cannot excuse the inability to create more than 3 years after signing the Act on the available care of a simple website.
I don't know if something like this was to be expected.
Whether I should have known at the age of 18 that government power could be contrary to the political campaigns that preceded it.
The elected office clearly has no predictable course, and our public talks will be shaped by an opposition political party and random events like the Newton massacre.
However, all the examples I have given above appear to a large extent to be the result of the administration’s own decision.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a confusing and unsorted alternative, and he seemed unable to consolidate his politics or position.
I felt that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of the next election, would fulfill the hopes we had once heard of.
Still, the return to 2008 – as Obama’s support fell below 45% this week – is becoming increasingly difficult through this book.
