Under the new bill, media companies can be fined up to 20 million Kenyan shills and individual journalists up to one million along with the risk of "decommissioning" or denied official journalistic accreditation.
The tribunal also has the right to seize the offender's property if the fine is not paid.
According to the Daily Nation, “even one fine is enough to destroy most radio stations.”
It is also reported that these measures can have a liquidating impact on what is called the Kenyan "live blogosphere."
Politicians know that when they silence the media, they can do whatever they want with impunity.
"You never know what might happen," wrote Nation journalist Mutuma Mathiu, describing Kenyan media as a key source of a system of mutual control and balance in public life.
"If we leave it to the politicians, they will bring the country to bankruptcy and throw us back to hunting and collecting," he wrote.
Lawmakers in Kenya have been the target of public criticism in the past.
In May, they voted to repeal cuts ordered by the national pay agency and to restore their fat salaries of around 532,000 untaxed shillings a month, making them among the tallest in the world.
